<h1>Complete Saudi Arabia Expat Guide 2026</h1>
<p>Saudi Arabia is in the middle of the most ambitious national transformation attempt in modern history. Vision 2030, the comprehensive reform program championed by Crown Prince Mohammed bin Salman, is simultaneously reshaping the kingdom's economy, social fabric, urban landscape, and international standing. The scale of investment is staggering: over USD 1 trillion committed to mega-projects that include NEOM, a futuristic development on the Red Sea coast; The Line, a 170-kilometer linear city designed to house 9 million people; Qiddiya, an entertainment destination covering 334 square kilometers; the Red Sea tourism project spanning 28,000 square kilometers of pristine coastline; and Diriyah Gate, a cultural heritage development at the birthplace of the Saudi state. These are not conceptual proposals sitting on drawing boards. Construction cranes, work camps, and concrete foundations are visible across the kingdom's landscape, and tens of thousands of international professionals are already at work bringing these projects to reality.</p>

<p>For the expatriate professional evaluating a Gulf career in 2026, Saudi Arabia's proposition has shifted dramatically from what it was even five years ago. The kingdom charges zero personal income tax on employment income, and while its 15% VAT rate is the highest in the Gulf, the substantially lower cost of living compared to the UAE means that most expats in Saudi Arabia still save more in absolute terms than their counterparts in Dubai. The social environment has transformed since 2017: cinemas have opened for the first time, concerts by major international artists draw hundreds of thousands, mixed-gender dining and entertainment are now routine, and women drive, work, and participate in public life with a freedom that would have been unimaginable a decade ago. The combination of career opportunities that are genuinely unique to this moment in history, a financial structure that rewards savings, and a society that is rapidly modernizing makes Saudi Arabia one of the most compelling destinations available to internationally mobile professionals.</p>

<div class="not-prose my-8"><CostOfLivingSimulator client:visible defaultCity="riyadh" /></div>

<h2>The Vision 2030 Opportunity</h2>
<p>Vision 2030 is not a single project but a comprehensive national strategy encompassing economic diversification, social reform, and international repositioning. The Public Investment Fund, one of the world's largest sovereign wealth funds with assets exceeding USD 930 billion, is the primary financial engine behind the transformation. PIF's portfolio companies and direct investments span tourism, entertainment, technology, sports, real estate, and financial services, creating demand for international talent across an extraordinarily wide range of disciplines.</p>

<p>NEOM, the most ambitious of the giga-projects, is envisioned as a new model for sustainable urban living on a 26,500-square-kilometer site on the Red Sea coast. The Line, NEOM's signature development, aims to create a car-free linear city powered entirely by renewable energy. Whether these visions are fully realized as currently described, the construction activity, engineering challenges, and project management demands are generating employment for architects, civil engineers, environmental scientists, urban planners, IT specialists, and hospitality professionals at salary levels that reflect the urgency and ambition of the endeavor. Qiddiya, the entertainment mega-destination southwest of Riyadh, will include the kingdom's first theme parks, a motorsport facility, golf courses, and nature reserves. The Red Sea project is creating luxury resort infrastructure along a previously undeveloped coastline, requiring hospitality managers, marine biologists, construction engineers, and tourism professionals.</p>
<VisaProcessFlow country="saudi-arabia" />

<h2>Cost of Living</h2>
<p>Saudi Arabia offers the lowest cost of living among the three major Gulf expat destinations. A one-bedroom apartment in <a href="/saudi-arabia/riyadh/" class="text-brand-600 dark:text-brand-400 hover:underline">Riyadh</a> costs SAR 2,500 to SAR 5,000 per month, roughly 40% to 60% less than comparable accommodation in Dubai. Family villas in residential compound communities range from SAR 8,000 to SAR 20,000 monthly. Groceries are affordable at SAR 800 to SAR 1,800 per month. Dining ranges from SAR 15 for a budget meal to SAR 150 at mid-range restaurants. Petrol is exceptionally cheap at approximately SAR 2.18 per liter. <a href="/saudi-arabia/utilities/" class="text-brand-600 dark:text-brand-400 hover:underline">Utilities</a> through the Saudi Electricity Company and National Water Company are subsidized and typically cost SAR 300 to SAR 800 monthly.</p>

<p>The kingdom's 15% VAT rate is the highest in the GCC and does add noticeably to grocery bills, restaurant tabs, and retail purchases. On a monthly spend of SAR 5,000 in taxable goods, you pay SAR 750 in VAT. However, the dramatically lower base prices for housing, transportation, and daily essentials mean that the total cost of living in Saudi Arabia remains well below Dubai or even Doha. For many professionals, especially those receiving employer-provided compound housing, Saudi Arabia offers the strongest absolute savings potential of any Gulf country.</p>

<h2>Working Environment</h2>
<p>The Saudi work week follows a Sunday to Thursday schedule, with Friday and Saturday forming the weekend. This shifted from the traditional Thursday-Friday weekend in 2022, aligning the kingdom more closely with global business schedules. Maximum working hours are eight per day or 48 per week, reduced during Ramadan for Muslim employees. Annual leave begins at 21 days per year, increasing to 30 days after five years of continuous service with the same employer. The Qiwa platform has digitized many employment processes, from contract registration to salary protection monitoring. For detailed labor law information, see our partner site's <a href="https://taxfreesalaries.com/saudi-arabia/employment-contracts/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Saudi employment contracts guide</a>.</p>

<h2>Social Transformation</h2>
<p>Saudi Arabia's social environment has changed more rapidly than that of any other Gulf state since the reform program began in 2017. The opening of cinemas, the hosting of concerts featuring international artists from Beyonce to Metallica, the Formula 1 Saudi Arabian Grand Prix, mixed-gender dining, and the expansion of tourist visa eligibility have collectively created a social landscape that bears little resemblance to the kingdom of a decade ago. Riyadh Season, an annual entertainment festival running from October through March, attracts millions of visitors with themed zones, immersive experiences, and celebrity performances. AlUla, the ancient heritage site in northwestern Saudi Arabia, has emerged as a cultural and tourist destination of global significance. While Saudi Arabia remains a country with Islamic values at its core, and visitors and residents are expected to show respect for local customs and traditions, the pace of social opening has been genuinely remarkable.</p>

<h2>Healthcare</h2>
<p>Healthcare in Saudi Arabia operates through both the Ministry of Health public hospital network and a growing private sector. All employers are legally required to provide <a href="/saudi-arabia/healthcare/" class="text-brand-600 dark:text-brand-400 hover:underline">medical insurance</a> through CCHI-approved providers before the Iqama is issued. Major private hospital groups include Dr. Sulaiman Al Habib, Saudi German Hospitals, and Dallah Health. King Faisal Specialist Hospital and Research Centre is the premier medical institution in the country. The Saudi Commission for Health Specialties regulates professional licensing for all healthcare workers. Healthcare coverage standards and facility quality have improved substantially as part of the kingdom's broader modernization effort.</p>

<h2>Education</h2>
<p><a href="/saudi-arabia/education/" class="text-brand-600 dark:text-brand-400 hover:underline">International schools</a> in Saudi Arabia have expanded notably over the past five years. Riyadh, <a href="/saudi-arabia/jeddah/" class="text-brand-600 dark:text-brand-400 hover:underline">Jeddah</a>, and the Eastern Province (<a href="/saudi-arabia/dammam/" class="text-brand-600 dark:text-brand-400 hover:underline">Khobar/Dhahran</a>) offer the most options, with British, American, IB, and other curricula available. School fees range from SAR 15,000 to SAR 65,000 annually depending on curriculum and institution. KAUST, the King Abdullah University of Science and Technology, is a world-class research university operating on its own campus near Jeddah. Many residential compounds maintain proximity to international schools, and school transport is widely available at SAR 3,000 to SAR 6,000 per year.</p>

<h2>Banking and Financial Setup</h2>
<p>Opening a bank account requires your Iqama, passport, and an employer salary certificate. Major banks for expatriates include Al Rajhi Bank, Saudi National Bank, Riyad Bank, and SABB. Most banks offer digital onboarding once your Iqama number is active in the system. The Wage Protection System requires employers to pay salaries electronically through GOSI-linked accounts. International money transfers are available through bank wire transfers and exchange houses including Al Rajhi Exchange and Western Union, with exchange houses typically offering better rates for common remittance corridors to India, Pakistan, the Philippines, and Egypt. STC Pay and other digital wallets have become popular for domestic peer-to-peer transfers.</p>

<h2>Visa and Residency Options</h2>
<p>Saudi Arabia's visa landscape offers several pathways. The standard work visa and Iqama system, administered through the Qiwa platform, remains the most common route. Premium Residency provides a self-sponsored alternative at SAR 800,000 permanent or SAR 100,000 annually. Tourist e-visas are available for over 50 nationalities, and business visit visas have been streamlined. Family sponsorship requires a minimum salary of SAR 4,000 per month. For comprehensive visa information, see our <a href="/saudi-arabia/visa-guide/">Saudi Arabia Visa Guide</a>.</p>

<h2>Insurance and Employee Benefits</h2>
<p>Standard employment packages in Saudi Arabia typically include housing allowance (often 25% of basic salary), annual round-trip airfare, transportation allowance, and end-of-service gratuity. Senior roles frequently add education allowance for children, furnished compound accommodation, club memberships, and performance bonuses. When evaluating a Saudi job offer, always request a full breakdown beyond the headline salary, as housing, education, and insurance benefits can add 30% to 50% to the total package value. Health insurance through CCHI-approved providers is mandatory, with annual costs ranging from SAR 2,500 for basic plans to SAR 10,000 or more for comprehensive coverage.</p>

<h2>Practical Expat Tips for Daily Life</h2>
<p>The kingdom operates on the Hijri calendar for government matters, though most businesses use the Gregorian calendar. Government offices and banks close during the five daily prayer times, each lasting approximately 20 to 30 minutes. Planning errands between prayer times helps navigate daily life efficiently. Summer temperatures regularly exceed 45 degrees in Riyadh, making air conditioning essential and outdoor activities impractical from June through September. The winter months from November through March offer pleasant weather. <a href="/saudi-arabia/telecom/" class="text-brand-600 dark:text-brand-400 hover:underline">Mobile connectivity</a> is excellent, with STC, Mobily, and Zain offering competitive data plans. Most government services are accessible through the Tawakkalna and Absher apps.</p>

<h2>Transportation</h2>
<p>Saudi Arabia is car-oriented, and most expatriates purchase or lease a vehicle shortly after arrival. Petrol costs approximately SAR 2.18 per liter. The Riyadh Metro is expanding with six lines covering 176 kilometers. Ride-hailing through Uber and Careem is available in major cities. The Haramain High-Speed Railway connects Makkah, Jeddah, and Madinah. Domestic flights through Saudia, flynas, and flyadeal connect cities across the kingdom. Speed cameras and the Saher traffic system are extensive, with fines managed through Absher.</p>

<h2>Understanding Saudization in Practice</h2>
<p>The Nitaqat program has practical implications for every expatriate. Companies are classified into Platinum, Green, Yellow, and Red bands based on their Saudi national employment ratio. Platinum companies enjoy the fastest visa processing and fewest restrictions. Red companies cannot issue new work visas. Before accepting an offer, ask about your employer's Nitaqat status, as it affects visa processing, Iqama renewal, and your employer's ability to retain international staff. Technology, specialized engineering, healthcare, and senior management remain accessible to international hires due to limited domestic talent supply in these fields.</p>

<h2>Cultural Expectations and Social Norms</h2>
<p>Business meetings often begin with extended greetings and social conversation, and building personal rapport is valued in Saudi professional culture. During Ramadan, working hours are reduced by two hours per day, and non-Muslim expatriates should refrain from eating, drinking, and smoking in public during fasting hours. The weekend shifted to Friday and Saturday in 2022, aligning with global business schedules. Dress codes are generally conservative but vary by employer. Women are no longer required to wear an abaya in public, though modest dress is expected in most settings outside residential compounds.</p>

<h2>Compound Living and Housing Options</h2>
<p>Residential compounds are gated communities offering swimming pools, fitness centers, playgrounds, restaurants, and social clubs within a secure perimeter. Major compounds in Riyadh include the Diplomatic Quarter, Al Hamra, and Arizona compound. Compound rental costs range from SAR 80,000 to SAR 200,000 annually. For expatriates preferring greater independence, standalone apartments and villas are available in residential neighborhoods at significantly lower prices. Understanding whether your employer provides housing directly, offers a housing allowance, or includes housing in the basic salary is important when evaluating offers, as housing allowance is included in the Saudi end-of-service gratuity calculation.</p>

